      <title>Russia launches its first floating nuclear power plant to the arctic</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANA massive floating nuclear power plant is now on its way to an Arctic port, after Russia's state nuclear corporation Rosatom launched the nuclear plant over the weekend.Russian officials say the Akademik Lomonosov is set to become the first series of floating nuclear power plants Russia plans to develop.The portable plant is not self-propelled and must be towed to the desired location. It is designed to provide energy to port cities and offshore gas and oil-extracting platforms.The floating nuclear power plant will be towed from St. Petersburg and around Norway to a Russian town called Murmansk to take on nuclear fuel. From Murmansk, the $232 million nuclear plant will head to the Arctic to power the oil-industry town of Pevek.With two nuclear reactors, the nuclear plant will produce up to 70 MW[a] of electricity, enough to power a city of 100,000 inhabitants.Rosatom says the nuclear plant is designed with the great margin of safety that exceeds all possible threats and makes nuclear reactors 'invincible' for tsunamis and other natural disasters.Rosatom also added that the floating nuclear plant meets all the requirements of the International Atomic Energy Agency and do not pose any threats to the environment.Despite such reassurances, Greenpeace nuclear expert Jan Haverkamp told Engadget that having nuclear reactors moving around the Arctic Ocean creates a obvious threat to a fragile environment which is already affected by climate change.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Akademik Lomonosov against a wireframe background2. Akademik Lomonosov docked3. The power plant towed by another ship4. The plant powering an oil drilling platform5. Show the power plant travelling from St. Petersburg to Murmansk to load nuclear fuel6. See the $233 million power plant head to the Arctic to power Pevek7. Representation of the plant powering a city with 200,000 inhabitants8. Show the power plant is disaster-proofed9. Show the power plant meets requirements from International Atomic Energy Agency and does not hurt the environment VOICEOVER (in English): "According to Russia officials, the Akademik Lomonosov is set to become the first series of floating nuclear power plants Russia plans to develop.""The portable plant is not self-propelled and must be towed to the desired location.""It is intended to provide energy energy to port cities and offshore gas and oil-extracting platforms.""The floating nuclear power plant will be towed from St. Petersburg and around Norway to a Russian town called Murmansk to take on nuclear fuel.""From Murmansk, the $232 million nuclear plant will head to the Arctic to power the oil-industry town of Pevek.""With two nuclear reactors, floating the nuclear plant will produce up to 70 MW[b] of electricity, enough to power a city with 100,000 inhabitants.""Rosatom says the nuclear plant is designed with the great margin of safety that exceeds all possible threats and makes nuclear reactors 'invincible' for tsunamis and other natural disasters.""Rosatom also added that the floating nuclear plant meets all the requirements of the International Atomic Energy Agency and do not pose any threats to the environment." SOURCES: ENDGADGET, ROSATOMhttps://www.engadget.com/amp/2018/04/30/russia-floating-nuclear-power-plant/http://www.rosatom.ru/en/press-centre/news/the-world-s-only-floating-power-unit-akademik-lomonosov-takes-the-sea/***]]></description>
