      <title>Hawaii approves bill banning sunscreen with reef-killing chemicals</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANThe same sunscreen that's protecting our skin is apparently harming the marine ecosystem.The Honolulu Star Advertiser reports that Hawaii lawmakers passed a bill on Tuesday prohibiting the sale and distribution of sunscreen that contains two chemicals known to damage coral reefs.Popular sunscreen brands like Coppertone, Banana Boat, and Hawaiian Tropic have been found to contain oxybenzone and octinoxate, which filter and absorb UV rays.A 2015 study led by the Haereticus Environmental Laboratory in Virginia looked at reefs in Hawaii, the U.S. Virgin Islands, and Israel, and found that the chemicals caused bleaching by eliminating algae and nutrients in the coral.According to NPR, just one drop of sunscreen is reportedly enough to damage delicate reef systems and disrupt the development of marine wildlife.Sunscreen manufacturers and retail and health reps who oppose the ban claim banning the chemicals could leave millions vulnerable to harmful sun exposure.The bill will need to be signed by the governor to pass into legislation. If it does, Hawaii will become the first U.S. state to enact a law of this kind, which will take effect on January 1, 2021.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Hawaii to ban sale of sunscreens containing reef-killing chemicals2. Oxybenzone and octinoxate in sunscreen filter and absorb UV rays3. Chemicals eliminates algae, nutrients in coral, causing coral bleaching4. Chemicals disrupt development of other marine organismsVOICEOVER (in English): "Hawaii lawmakers have passed a bill prohibiting the sale and distribution of sunscreen that contains two chemicals known to damage coral reefs.""Several popular sunscreen brands have been found to contain oxybenzone and octinoxate, which filter and absorb UV rays.""A 2015 study of reefs in Hawaii, the U.S. Virgin Islands, and Israel found that the chemicals caused bleaching by eliminating algae and nutrients in the coral.""Just one drop of sunscreen is reportedly enough to damage delicate reef systems and disrupt the development of marine wildlife."SOURCES: Honolulu Star Advertiser, Washington Post, University of Central Florida, NPRhttp://www.staradvertiser.com/2018/05/01/breaking-news/bill-banning-chemicals-in-sunscreens-passes-in-state-legislature/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2018/05/02/hawaii-might-be-about-to-ban-your-favorite-sunscreen-to-protect-its-coral-reefs/?utm_term=.43b4349da88bhttp://today.ucf.edu/lathering-up-with-sunscreen-may-protect-against-cancer-killing-coral-reefs-worldwide/https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2018/05/02/607765760/hawaii-approves-bill-banning-sunscreen-believed-to-kill-coral-reefs***]]></description>
