      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANA new study says large predators are moving into unexpected areas in order to recolonize former hunting grounds taken over by humans. According to Duke University researchers in a press release, large predator sightings such as alligators on the beach, killer whales in rivers and mountain lions in open fields are a sign that local populations have rebounded thanks to conservation efforts. The study, published in the journal Current Biology, found that alligators and sea otters were actually re-colonizing ecosystems that had been prime hunting grounds before humans decimated their populations. By collating data from other studies and government reports, Duke researchers found alligators, see otters, river otters, gray whales, gray wolves, mountain lions, orangutans and bald eagles populations were either as abundant or more abundant in "novel" habitats than in traditional ones. Rebounding numbers have shown that several large predators once thought to be highly habitat specific, are actually quite adaptable. RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Alligator on beach, killer whale in river, and mountain lion in open field2. Alligator and sea otter feeding3. Populations of large predators that have increasedVOICEOVER (in English): "According to Duke University researchers in a press release, large predator sightings such as alligators on the beach, killer whales in rivers and mountain lions in open fields are a sign that local populations have rebounded thanks to conservation efforts." "The study, published in the journal Current Biology, found that alligators and sea otters were actually re-colonizing ecosystems that had been prime hunting grounds before humans decimated their populations." "Duke scientists alligators, see otters, river otters, gray whales, gray wolves, mountain lions, orangutans and bald eagles populations were either as abundant or more abundant in "novel" habitats than in traditional ones." SOURCES: CBS Denver, Duke Universityhttp://denver.cbslocal.com/2018/05/08/animals-predators-odd-places/https://eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2018-05/du-aot050718.php***]]></description>
