      <title>Massive wave is largest ever recorded in southern hemisphere</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANNew Zealand scientists claim a monster wave detected during a storm is the largest ever recorded in the southern hemisphere.The BBC reports that according to the Meteorological Service of New Zealand, a solitary buoy measured a 78-foot wave in the Southern Ocean off Campbell Island on the night of May 9.The massive wave is roughly the same height as an seven-storey building, and just a bit taller than five double decker buses stacked on top of each other.It beat out the previous record holder  a 72-foot swell recorded in Tasmania in 2012.The wave formed during a storm, in which the significant wave height or the average of the top third of waves measured from crest to trough reached over 48 feet.Though a record for the Southern Ocean, larger wave heights have been identified in the northern hemisphere.Scientists say it's possible the storm generated even bigger waves that weren't recorded by the buoy, which operates for only 20 minutes every three hours.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. 23.8-meter-tall wave recorded by buoy in Southern Ocean2. Wave is as tall as an 7-storey building or five stacked double decker buses 3. Significant wave height measuring 14.9 meters4. Buoy records for only 20 minutes every three hoursVOICEOVER (in English): "According to the Meteorological Service of New Zealand, a solitary buoy measured a 78-foot wave in the Southern Ocean off Campbell Island on the night of May 9.""The massive wave is roughly the same height as a 7-storey building, and just a bit taller than five double decker buses stacked on top of each other.""The wave formed during a storm, in which the significant wave height or the average of the top third of waves measured from crest to trough reached over 48 feet.""Scientists say it's possible the storm generated even bigger waves that weren't recorded by the buoy, which operates for only 20 minutes every three hours."SOURCES: BBC, Sydney Morning Herald, ABC Newshttp://www.bbc.com/news/world-australia-44078255https://www.smh.com.au/environment/weather/surf-s-really-up-largest-wave-ever-recorded-in-southern-ocean-20180510-p4zej6.htmlhttp://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-11/largest-wave-ever-recorded-in-southern-ocean/9751680***]]></description>
