      <title>Bug in cell phone tracking firm's website exposed locations of American users in real-time</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANA company that collects real-time location data of millions of cell phone users throughout North America had a bug on its website that let anyone see where a person was located without having to obtain consent. LocationSmart is a data aggregator and says it has "direct connections" to cell carriers to obtain location information from nearby cell towers, according to ZDNet.The website has a trial-page that allows interested customers to test the accuracy of the system. The page requires explicit consent from the user before location data can be collected by sending a one-time text message.  However, a bug on the website discovered by Carnegie Mellon University researcher Robert Xiao, allowed anyone to track someone's location without their consent. Xiao told ZDNet, a simple bug allowed a person to skip the consent section and jump straight to the location. In a statement from spokesperson Brenda Schafer, LocationSmart "confirmed that the vulnerability was not exploited prior to May 16, and did not result in any customer information being obtained without their permission."Xiao said the bug may have exposed almost every cell phone user in North America, around 200 million customers, ZDNet reported. According to a LocationSmart statement, the bug has been resolved and the demo has been disabled. RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. LocationSmart claims it can obtain location data from cell carrier towers2. Cell phone users being tracked without their consent3. Depiction of cell tower triangulation to locate users4. Bug exposing cell phone data for 200 million customersVOICEOVER (in English): "LocationSmart is a data aggregator and claims it has 'direct connections' to cell carriers to obtain location information from nearby cell towers throughout North America. A bug on its website lets anyone see where a person was located without having to obtain consent." "According to ZDNet, the website has a trial-page that allows customers to test the accuracy of the system.The page requires explicit consent from the user before location data can be collected by sending a one-time text message." "Carnegie Mellon University researcher Robert Xiao found a bug that allowed a person to skip the consent section and jump straight to the location." "Xiao said the bug may have exposed almost every cell phone user in North America, around 200 million customers."SOURCES: ZDNet, LocationSmarthttps://www.zdnet.com/article/cell-phone-tracking-firm-exposed-millions-of-americans-real-time-locations/https://www.zdnet.com/article/us-cell-carriers-selling-access-to-real-time-location-data/https://www.locationsmart.com/company/news/statement-regarding-recently-reported-security-incident***]]></description>
